Project: User Value Segmentation (The 6-Tier "Precious Metals" Model)¶

1. Problem Statement¶

Objective: We want to segment our users to deeply understand their spending behavior and deploy targeted strategies to maximize their lifetime value.

The Challenge:

  • The "Average" Fallacy: A simple average spending metric fails because our data follows a Power Law (80/20 rule). A small number of top spenders skew the mean, making "average" strategies ineffective.
  • Labeling Bias: Not all high spenders are "Resellers." We need a neutral, value-based hierarchy that respects all user types (from casual buyers to power users).
  • Operational Inefficiency: We currently lack a data-driven way to allocate resourcesspending too much time on low-value users while under-serving our VIPs.

2. The Methodology: Hybrid Statistical Split¶

To solve this, we utilize a Hybrid Box-Cox & Head/Tail Breaks model to identify 6 natural tiers of user value.

  • Box-Cox Transformation: Normalizes the skewed spending data into a bell curve to find statistical outliers.
  • Recursive Breaks: Identifies the "fractal" nature of spending, isolating the top 1% of the top 1%.

3. The 6-Tier Value Split¶

Our analysis identifies 6 distinct user tiers based on Daily Average NMV:

Tier Segment Name Spend Threshold ($) The Persona (Behavior)
6 Platinum >$937 Top Spenders. High volume, high frequency. The economic engines of the platform.
5 Gold $288 - $937 Very High Spenders. Consistent, professional-level volume.
4 Silver $66 - $288 Above-Average. Serious active users with significant monthly spend.
3 Bronze $19 - $66 Average. Regular active users, the "Middle Class" of the platform.
2 Copper $3 - $19 Below-Average. Occasional buyers or low-value sellers.
1 Starter <$3 Lowest Spenders. Low frequency, testing, or dormant.

4. Strategic Goals¶

We will map these segments to three core strategic pillars:

  • Strategy X: Retention (Platinum & Gold)
    • Goal: 0% Churn.
    • Action: White-glove account management, priority support, exclusivity.
  • Strategy Y: Growth (Silver & Bronze)
    • Goal: Ascension. Move them up the metal ladder.
    • Action: Value-based incentives ("Reach Silver Status"), loyalty rewards.
  • Strategy Z: Efficiency (Copper & Starter)
    • Goal: Automation. Minimize cost-to-serve.
    • Action: Self-service help center, automated nurture campaigns.

3. Data Loading & Preprocessing¶

In this section, we load the raw user data and prepare it for statistical analysis.

  • Input: Reseller Split.xlsx (Contains User IDs, Day Avg NMV, Total NMV).
  • Cleaning: We remove any users with 0 or negative spend. The Box-Cox transformation requires strictly positive values ($x > 0$).

5. Visualization: The "Revenue Density" Proof¶

We visualize the data to validate our 6-tier split.

  • Chart 1 (Revenue Density): A weighted histogram showing where the money is. It reveals that the bulk of our revenue sits in the far-right "Mega Whale" tail, which is invisible on standard user-count charts.
  • Chart 2 (Segment Value): A direct comparison of Total Revenue per Tier, proving that the top 1.5% of users (Platinum) drive ~81% of the business value.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

# 1. PREPARE THE DATA AGGREGATION
# We group by segment to get the summary stats
# Ensure the order is correct (Low Value -> High Value)
seg_order = ['1. Starter', '2. Copper', '3. Bronze', '4. Silver', '5. Gold', '6. Platinum']
summary = df_clean.groupby('Segment').agg(
    Total_Revenue=('TOTAL_NMV', 'sum'),
    User_Count=('DAY_AVG_NMV', 'count')
).reindex(seg_order).fillna(0)

# Calculate Percentages for context
summary['Rev_Share'] = summary['Total_Revenue'] / summary['Total_Revenue'].sum()
summary['User_Share'] = summary['User_Count'] / summary['User_Count'].sum()

# 2. SETUP THE DUAL AXIS CHART
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 7))
ax2 = ax1.twinx()  # Create the second axis sharing the same X

# Style settings
bar_color = '#1f4e79'   # Professional Navy Blue for Revenue
line_color = '#d62728'  # Alert Red for Headcount
width = 0.6

# 3. PLOT LAYERS
# Layer 1: Revenue Bars (The "Value")
bars = ax1.bar(summary.index, summary['Total_Revenue'], color=bar_color, 
               alpha=0.8, width=width, label='Total Revenue ($)')

# Layer 2: User Count Line (The "Volume")
# We plot this on the secondary axis
line = ax2.plot(summary.index, summary['User_Count'], color=line_color, 
                marker='o', linewidth=3, markersize=8, label='User Count (#)')

# 4. CUSTOMIZE AXES
# Axis 1 (Left - Revenue)
ax1.set_ylabel('Total Revenue ($)', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', color=bar_color)
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=bar_color)
ax1.yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: f'${x/1e6:.1f}M'))
ax1.set_ylim(0, summary['Total_Revenue'].max() * 1.2) # Give headroom for labels

# Axis 2 (Right - Users)
ax2.set_ylabel('Number of Users', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', color=line_color)
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=line_color)
ax2.yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: f'{x/1000:.0f}k'))
ax2.set_ylim(0, summary['User_Count'].max() * 1.2)
ax2.grid(False) # Turn off grid for secondary axis to avoid clutter

# 5. INTEGRATE THRESHOLDS INTO X-AXIS LABELS
# We reconstruct the labels to include the $ cuts calculated previously
# Note: We assume 'usd_breaks' exists from your previous step. 
# If exact matching is tricky, we can just list the tiers.
threshold_labels = []
current_breaks = [0] + usd_breaks # Add 0 for Starter start
for i, name in enumerate(seg_order):
    # Get the "Start" of this tier
    floor_val = current_breaks[i] if i < len(current_breaks) else usd_breaks[-1]
    label_str = f"{name.split('. ')[1]}\n(>${floor_val:.0f})"
    threshold_labels.append(label_str)

ax1.set_xticklabels(threshold_labels, fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')

# 6. ANNOTATIONS (The "Story")
# Label the Revenue Bars
for i, v in enumerate(summary['Total_Revenue']):
    if v > 0:
        ax1.text(i, v, f"${v/1e6:.1f}M\n({summary['Rev_Share'].iloc[i]:.0%})", 
                 ha='center', va='bottom', color=bar_color, fontweight='bold', fontsize=10)

# Label the User Counts (only for the extremes to reduce clutter)
for i, v in enumerate(summary['User_Count']):
    # Label first and last, or peaks
    if i == 0 or i == 5 or v == summary['User_Count'].max():
        ax2.text(i, v, f"{v:,.0f}\nUsers", 
                 ha='center', va='bottom', color=line_color, fontsize=9, fontweight='bold',
                 bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.3", fc='white', ec=line_color, alpha=0.8))

# Title
plt.title('Revenue by Tier (Bar) & Spend Distribution (Line)', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', pad=20)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

6. Stakeholder Buy-in: The Strategic Plan¶

The Verdict: Our analysis proves that 81% of our revenue is generated by just 1,300 "Platinum" users ($937+ daily spend). The "Long Tail" of 66,000+ users contributes less than 5% of our revenue.

The "Precious Metals" Strategy: We propose a radical shift in resource allocation based on three pillars (X, Y, Z):

Strategy X: RETENTION (Protect the Fort)¶

  • Target: Platinum (> $937) & **Gold** ($288 - $937).
  • Why: These ~3,000 users are the platform's engine (88% of Total Revenue). Losing one is costly.
  • Action Items:
    1. Concierge Onboarding: Direct phone access for Platinum members.
    2. Risk Monitoring: Automated alerts if their daily volume drops by >10%.
    3. Bespoke Rate Cards: Volume-based fee reductions to prevent churn to competitors.

Strategy Y: GROWTH (Move the Middle)¶

  • Target: Silver ($66 - $288) & Bronze ($19 - $66).
  • Why: These ~15,000 users have proven product-market fit but lack scale.
  • Action Items:
    1. "Path to Gold" Gamification: "Sell $500 more this week to unlock Gold Status."
    2. Bulk Tools: Unlock API access for Silver tier to help them list faster.
    3. Education: Monthly webinars on "How to scale your inventory."

Strategy Z: EFFICIENCY (Automate the Rest)¶

  • Target: Copper ($3 - $19) & Starter (< $3).
  • Why: These ~66,000 users create high operational noise but low financial value.
  • Action Items:
    1. Self-Service Only: Remove the "Contact Support" button; replace with Help Center.
    2. Automated Fraud Checks: Strict rules to block bad actors without human review.
    3. Nurture Loops: Automated email courses to wake up dormant users.

Next Steps¶

  1. Tag Users: Run the script to tag all User IDs with their new "Metal" status in the CRM.
  2. Pilot: Launch "Strategy X" (Concierge Service) for the top 100 Platinum users next week.
  3. Measure: Track the migration rate (e.g., % of Silver users becoming Gold) monthly.
